title: Build a Content Pack using Maven
content:
Develop your custom CloudSlang Content Packs based on the example_project template provided in this topic.

The project contains the three main components required for building a Content Pack:

  • a parent project: example_project
  • a module containing the source code: example_project_sources
  • a module containing the resources files: example_project_cp

Prerequisites

Install and set up Maven 3.3.9. Since CloudSlang is a maven-based project, this is required for building the project. Maven 3.3.9 is the only supported version.

Set up and first run

  1. Download the example_project from Github.
  2. Clone the project and import it into your development environment.
  3. Build the project using Maven 3.3.9.
  4. Upload the .JAR file to Central or Designer. You can find the .JAR file in the Target folder of the example_project_cp module.

Build your project

To have a valid project to build, customize the following components of the example project:

The Parent Project (example_project)

A valid Content Pack requires a parent project that includes:  

  • a module with the source code of the operations: example_project_sources 
  • a module with the .SL file resources for the operations implemented above: example_project_cp.

Rename the project

To rename the parent project, change its title and the artifactId value in the pom.xml file available for the parent project and in the pom.xml file available for the Resources module:

 

Configure the project

You can configure the following properties in the pom.xml file of the parent project:

  • project’s GAV (groupId, artifactId, version)
  • packaging type (for the parent project this is pom)
  • project name and description
  • SDK and JDL versions used, Maven-specific properties, source encoding
  • build plug-ins required for building the Content Pack
  • modules that need to be included in the Content Pack

Create a new module

To create a new module in IntelliJ, right-click on the project’s name and choose New > Module. This creates a new module inside the parent project with the following structure:

To convert an existing directory to a module in the Project Structure window click + > Import module.  Here you can create the required structure by manually adding the folders tree and the pom.xml file.

All the modules that need to be included in the Content Pack have to be specified in the parent project’s pom.xml file:

The Source Code Module (example_project_sources)

The Source code module must contain:

  • a folder named SRC for the source code of the .SL operations. We recommend using the same folder structure used in the example_project: src > main > java > io > cloudslang > content  > YOUR_INTEGRATION_NAME
  • (Optional) a folder named Test for the unit tests. If you create this folder, make sure to use the same structure as in the example_project: test > java > io > cloudslang > content > YOUR_INTEGRATION_NAME
  • a pom.xml file which defines the following:
    • GAV information for the module: groupId, artifactId, version.
    • The packaging type. For example, the example_project_sources module is packed in a .JAR file.
    • dependencies versions, including Maven dependencies versions, source encoding and other properties.
    • dependencies required for building and executing the source code.
    • the plug-ins required for the .JAR build.

To rename the Sources module, change its title in the IDE and in the module’s pom.xml file:

After you build the Sources module, a new folder called Target is created inside the module. This folder contains a .JAR file with the compiled code. Set the GroupId, ArtifactId and Version information in the GAV attribute of the .SL file: 

The Resources Module (example_project_cp)

The Resources module must use the following folder structure: src > main > resources > YOUR_PROJECT_NAME-project. Make sure to set the type of the folder to Resources from Intellij > Project Structure menu. 

To rename the Resources module change its name in the IDE and in the two pom.xml files available for the module. Make sure to use the following naming convention for the subfolder of the Resources directory: YOUR_PROJECT_NAME-project.

Folder structure

The following folders are mandatory in the module’s structure:

  • the Content folder with the Configuration and the Library subfolders
  • the Resource-bundles folder with the Cp.properties file 
  • the Contentpack.propertie file which contains some properties from the pom.xml files, such as: content pack name, version, description, publisher, date. 
  • the pom.xml file containing the GAV information for the module: groupId, artifactId, version

This structure is mandatory in order to build a valid Content Pack that can be afterwards uploaded to Central or Designer. Use consistent naming conventions and keep the same folder naming and structure in both modules.

To maintain the required folder structure, add a file called keep.structure in the Configuration folder.

Add your .SL files in the Library folder and make sure to use the following structure: Library > io > cloudslang > YOUR_INTEGRATION_NAME. Update the build version of all the .SL files in the project each time you build the sources Content Pack.

Make sure you define the following information in the pom.xml file for the module:

  • the parent project’s GAV information: groupId, artifactId, version
  • the module’s artifactId
  • some properties needed for the release and build time. The example project also specifies the remote and local signing properties.
  • the dependencies of the sources module that we have defined above:

  • the build resources located in the Resources folder set in this module:

  • the Maven plug-ins required to build the Content Pack.
